er, the face and hair where changed though (drag and drop):<br><br><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://members.tripod.com/ginzuishou/exp_ori.jpg">members.tripod.com/ginzui...xp_ori.jpg</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://members.tripod.com/ginzuishou/exp.jpg">members.tripod.com/ginzuishou/exp.jpg</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END-->     <p><p><FONT face=Verdana size=2>Brian Bork</FONT><center><p><FONT face=Verdana size=1><u>Quote</u></FONT><br><FONT face=Verdana size=1>"Certo, un diavol dell'inferno <br>Qui il ha fatti capitar."</FONT><br><FONT face=Verdana size=1>Le Nozze di Figaro</FONT></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ubrianbork.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brian Bork</A> at: 3/26/02 8:42:46 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/udarkreaver66.showPublicProfile?language=EN>darkreaver66</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(3/26/02 11:16:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5604.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://liquid2k.com/darkreaver/images/avatar5.jpg  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Classicists are always right ^_~</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  nice!  geting rid of the lines really does make a pic more painting-like <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>One thing I'm wondering though is why you bothered to shade in pencil when you knew that you were going to over it with cg....outline would be fine as a reference I think.  I still think that the highlights should be somewhat warmer, but the skin has certainly acheived a sense of richness.  Although it's fine as it is, I suggest soothing it out more thean what you have now....some areas, like his right shoulder is really muddy looking....<br><br>mmm harder with more deatil?  I don't know....there's only one way to find out <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  I think the level of difficulty would be the some....it just would take longer.<br><br>again, if you get disoreinted with the lineart being presenat, you can ways keep it in another layer as a reference and get rid of it at the end.  you can try making it a semi-transparent lineart layer, so hat you can see under the black of the lines, or soemthing...I don't know. <p><a href=http://darkreaver.freeservers.com> <img src="http://liquid2k.com/darkreaver/images/bannner2.jpg" BORDER=0> </a>  <img src="http://liquid2k.com/darkreaver/images/booicon2.gif" BORDER=0> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uvellj001.showPublicProfile?language=EN>vellj001</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>PK Supporter</span><br> <font color=#336699>(3/26/02 11:45:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5604.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://vellj001.xoasis.com/0yibanner.jpg height=120 width=99></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Classicists are always right ^_~</span><hr size=1> Sweet really good work.  Looks quite like a classic painting.<br><br>Mainly I agree with DarkReavers comments especially on the the skin needing to be smoothed out.<br><br>I don't think it would be harder just yes it would take longer to tune right.  You might want to seek DarkStalkers opinion he is really good at turning heavily penciled pictures like this in really good classical looking paintings.  <p><a href="http://www.geocities.com/vellj001"><img src="http://vellj001.xoasis.com/00banner6.jpg"></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/udarkreaver66.showPublicProfile?language=EN>darkreaver66</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(3/26/02 11:51:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5604.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://liquid2k.com/darkreaver/images/avatar5.jpg  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Classicists are always right ^_~</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> You might want to seek DarkStalkers opinion he is really good at turning heavily penciled pictures like this in really good classical looking paintings. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>I'm not so sure about the 'classical' part....his method of coloring produces a more comicy, stylistic feeling, in my opinion....but that could just be the context of the coloring....<br><br>but I agree....darkstalker has experience with that sort of stuff (coloring shaded pic that is.)<br><br> <p><a href=http://darkreaver.freeservers.com> <img src="http://liquid2k.com/darkreaver/images/bannner2.jpg" BORDER=0> </a>  <img src="http://liquid2k.com/darkreaver/images/booicon2.gif" BORDER=0> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ubrianbork.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brian Bork</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(3/27/02 9:00:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5604.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Classicists are always right ^_~</span><hr size=1> Thanks Darkreaver and Vellj!<br><br>About the penciled under painting, it helped big time, strangely enough.  Because of it, I pretty much knew where and how to shade the figure, plus it was all in gritty pencil which gave it a bit of texture.  Plus, since pencil is gray/black, it was easy to paint over because I was using colour.  It's hard to explain really, it just seemed easier somehow.  <br><br>I think the problem is that I'm comparing it to trying to correct my Caravaggio image, which wasn't so easy to do because it had already been coloured and the line art was in the way.  However, when I removed the line art, it was too difficult without it because then everything became pretty blobby and undefined.  Line art covers a surprising amount of visual information, or makes up for it at least...<br><br>I did try making the line art semi-transparent but it was just the dynamics of that image.  It was, for all intense and purposes, finished.  For some reason I had great difficulty re-approaching it to correct it's problems.  Anyone else ever have this problem?<br><br>I'm putting aside the other image and have started a new one.  I'm going to do the image in pencil only (without any shading) and see how I do.  This time round I will make sure that I try and keep the skin and other colours from turning muddy as well (I don't like that look to much myself).  I'll soften out some of the areas too although I do want to try and maintain a brush stroke look.  I'll paint over the lines and use your suggestion, Reaver, and keep another copy of the image either as a layer or snapshot just in case. <p><p><FONT face=Verdana size=2>Brian Bork</FONT><center><p><FONT face=Verdana size=1><u>Quote</u></FONT><br><FONT face=Verdana size=1>"Certo, un diavol dell'inferno <br>Qui il ha fatti capitar."</FONT><br><FONT face=Verdana size=1>Le Nozze di Figaro